############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML The graph plots the number of cancer diagnoses in Oregon over time, and a trend-line has been drawn.
>> [@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>450)@]* <<
Estimate the slope of the trend-line.
[@KeyboardInstructions('You can type the unit as [|diagnoses/yr|]*.')@]**
[_]{$rate}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Do your best to identify two points on the line (which are not necessarily the plotted data points). With this line, it seems [`(2008,20000)`] and [`(2020,23000)`] are two such points.
[``` \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{(23000-20000)\,\text{diagnoses}}{(2020-2008)\,\text{yr}}=250\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{yr}} ```]
So the slope is about [`250`] diagnoses per year. This is only an estimate since we are not certain the two points we chose are actually on the line.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
